Yesterday, a virtual meeting was held between members of the White House Monkeypox and COVID-19 response teams, representatives from the CDC, college presidents, campus health officials, and student affairs professionals. The purpose of the meeting was to discuss best practices and measures for colleges and universities to prevent the spread of Monkeypox and COVID-19. Over 1,000 stakeholders from the higher education community participated in the meeting, with additional viewers joining via livestream. Federal officials provided practical guidance on how to ensure the safety of higher education institutions this fall, including strategies to identify and stop the spread of Monkeypox. They also addressed questions on how to respond to Monkeypox incidents and effectively communicate with students about vaccines, testing, and treatments. The discussion emphasized the importance of colleges and universities encouraging students, staff, and faculty to stay updated on their COVID-19 vaccines. Additionally, plans were made to administer the upcoming updated vaccines to campus communities in the fall, pending FDA and CDC decisions. Today, the CDC launched a new landing page with resources on Monkeypox for colleges, universities, and students.